{"title_page": "Kosmos 173", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 173\n| mission_type       = [[Antiballistic missile|ABM]] radar target\n| operator           = \n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-081A\n| SATCAT             = 02921\n| mission_duration   = 117 days\n\n| spacecraft_type    = [[DS-P1-Yu]]\n| manufacturer       = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n| launch_mass        = 325 kg\n\n| launch_date        = 24 August 1967, 04:59:49 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Kosmos-2I]] 63SM\n| launch_site        = [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|Plesetsk]], [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|133/1]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n\n| decay_date         = 17 December 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 24 August 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 261 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 471 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 71.0\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 91.86 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n'''Kosmos 173''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 173}} meaning ''Cosmos 173''), also known as '''DS-P1-Yu No.8''' was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[satellite]] which was used as a radar calibration target for tests of [[anti-ballistic missile]]s. It was built by the [[[[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]]], and launched in 1967 as part of the [[Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik]] programme.<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsp1yu.htm|title=DS-P1-Yu|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=9 August 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67kl9Q2Et?url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsp1yu.htm|archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kosmos-2I]] 63SM carrier rocket was used to launch Kosmos 173 from [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|Site 133/1]] at [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome]].<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web |url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> The launch occurred at 04:59:49 GMT on 24 August 1967, and resulted in Kosmos 173's successful deployment into [[low earth orbit]].<ref name=\"EA-K2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|title=Kosmos 2|last=Wade|first=Mark |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=9 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/690mZkz9v?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|archivedate=8 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nKosmos 173 was operated in an orbit with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|261|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|471|km}}, an [[inclination]] of 71.0\u00b0, and an [[orbital period]] of 91.86 minutes.<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\"/><ref name=\"JSR-SC\"/> It remained in orbit until it [[orbital decay|decayed]] and reentered the atmosphere on 17 December 1967.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> It was the ninth of seventy nine [[DS-P1-Yu]] satellites to be launched,<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\"/> and the eighth of seventy two to successfully reach orbit.<ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/ds-p1-yu.htm |title=DS-P1-Yu (11F618)|first=Gunter|last=Krebs|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[1967 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1967}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0173}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1967]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites|Kosmos 0173]]\n[[Category:1967 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik program]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name               = Kosmos 173\n| mission_type       = [[Antiballistic missile|ABM]] radar target\n| operator           = \n| COSPAR_ID          = 1967-081A\n| SATCAT             = 02921\n| mission_duration   = 100 days\n\n| spacecraft_type    = [[DS-P1-Yu]]\n| manufacturer       = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n| launch_mass        = 325 kg\n\n| launch_date        = 24 August 1967, 04:59:49 GMT\n| launch_rocket      = [[Kosmos-2I]] 63SM\n| launch_site        = [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|Plesetsk]], [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|133/1]]\n| launch_contractor  = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n\n| decay_date         = 17 December 1967\n\n| orbit_epoch        = 24 August 1967\n| orbit_reference    = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime       = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis    = 261 km\n| orbit_apoapsis     = 471 km\n| orbit_inclination  = 71.0\u00b0\n| orbit_period       = 91.86 minutes\n| apsis              = gee\n}}\n'''Kosmos 173''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 173}} meaning ''Cosmos 173''), also known as '''DS-P1-Yu No.8''' was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[satellite]] which was used as a radar calibration target for tests of [[anti-ballistic missile]]s. It was built by the [[[[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]]], and launched in 1967 as part of the [[Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik]] programme.<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsp1yu.htm|title=DS-P1-Yu|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=9 August 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67kl9Q2Et?url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsp1yu.htm|archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kosmos-2I]] 63SM carrier rocket was used to launch Kosmos 173 from [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome|Site 133/1]] at [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome]].<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web |url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> The launch occurred at 04:59:49 GMT on 24 August 1967, and resulted in Kosmos 173's successful deployment into [[low earth orbit]].<ref name=\"EA-K2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|title=Kosmos 2|last=Wade|first=Mark |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=9 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/690mZkz9v?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|archivedate=8 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nKosmos 173 was operated in an orbit with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|261|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|471|km}}, an [[inclination]] of 71.0\u00b0, and an [[orbital period]] of 91.86 minutes.<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\"/><ref name=\"JSR-SC\"/> It remained in orbit until it [[orbital decay|decayed]] and reentered the atmosphere on 17 December 1967.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref> It was the ninth of seventy nine [[DS-P1-Yu]] satellites to be launched,<ref name=\"EA-DSP1Yu\"/> and the eighth of seventy two to successfully reach orbit.<ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/ds-p1-yu.htm |title=DS-P1-Yu (11F618)|first=Gunter|last=Krebs|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[1967 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1967}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0173}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1967]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites|Kosmos 0173]]\n[[Category:1967 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik program]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosmos_173"}
{"title_page": "Baluta (autobiography)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Baluta''''' ([[Marathi language|Marathi]] \u092c\u0932\u0941\u0924\u0902) is an autobiography by the [[India]]n writer [[Daya Pawar]], written in the [[Marathi language]].<ref name=\"\u1e0c\u0101\u1e45ga\u1e37e1992\"> Dangale considers it a remarkable representative of the autobiography genre of Marathi Dalit literature.{{cite book|author=Arjuna \u1e0c\u0101\u1e45ga\u1e37e|title=Poisoned bread: translations from modern Marathi Dalit literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jKy28jPKZhEC&pg=PA255|accessdate=9 March 2012|year=1992|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-0-86311-254-6|pages=255}}</ref> According to Kalita, ''Baluta'' \"introduced autobiographical writing\" to [[Dalit literature]].<ref name=\"Kalit\u01012002\">{{cite book|author=Ar\u016bp\u0101 Pa\u1e6da\u1e43g\u012b\u1e8f\u0101 Kalit\u0101|title=Translating caste|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PpjAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Katha|isbn=978-81-87649-05-2|pages=241}}</ref> ''Baluta'' is seen by the ''Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature'' as an attempt by the writer to be personal yet \"objective and representative\", the title generalising the status of rural [[Dalit|untouchables]]. It records the writer's struggle for peace, a struggle with no chance of retaliation in \"word or deed\".<ref name=\"Datta2006\">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=The Encyclopaedia Of Indian Literature (Volume One (A To Devo)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA357|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1803-1|pages=357\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\nRao considers that ''Baluta'', as a representative of Dalit literature, was not just a faithful narration of the Dalit experience but also an \"ethical challenge\" to the \"caste Hindu\" whom it \"implicated\".<ref name=\"Rao2009\">{{cite book|author=Anupama Rao|title=The caste question: Dalits and the politics of modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tDRiJ3HZVPQC&pg=PA197|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=6 July 2009|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-25761-0|pages=197\u2013}}</ref> [[Sharmila Rege]] quotes [[Urmila Pawar]], who mentions the criticism of Dalit scholars that ''Baluta'' was shameful; Urmila rejects this criticism as based on lack of understanding.<ref name=\"Rege2006\">{{cite book|first=Sharmila |last=Rege |authorlink=Sharmila Rege|title=Writing caste, writing gender: reading Dalit women's testimonios|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Msaki69NQHsC&pg=PA292|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=2 July 2006|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-81-89013-01-1|pages=292}}</ref> According to ''The Encyclopaedia...'', it created the first anti-hero in [[Marathi literature]].<ref name=\"Datta2006\"/> ''Link'' mentions that ''Baluta'' \"created a sensation in the Marathi world for its frank and unique description of a life that the author lived in the ghettos of prostitutes, criminals, pimps and uprooted Dalit people, within and around the red light areas of the city of [[Mumbai|Bombay]].\"<ref name=\"Link: Indian newsmagazine\">{{cite book|title=Link: Indian newsmagazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=89YxAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=9 March 2012|year=1981|page=37}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian autobiographies]]\n[[Category:Dalit literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Baluta''''' ([[Marathi language|Marathi]] \u092c\u0932\u0941\u0924\u0902) is an autobiography by the [[India]]n writer [[Daya Pawar]], written in the [[Marathi language]].<ref name=\"\u1e0c\u0101\u1e45ga\u1e37e1992\"> Dangale considers it a remarkable representative of the autobiography genre of Marathi Dalit literature.{{cite book|author=Arjuna \u1e0c\u0101\u1e45ga\u1e37e|title=Poisoned bread: translations from modern Marathi Dalit literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jKy28jPKZhEC&pg=PA255|accessdate=9 March 2012|year=1992|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-0-86311-254-6|pages=255}}</ref> According to Kalita, ''Baluta'' \"introduced autobiographical writing\" to [[Dalit literature]].<ref name=\"Kalit\u01012002\">{{cite book|author=Ar\u016bp\u0101 Pa\u1e6da\u1e43g\u012b\u1e8f\u0101 Kalit\u0101|title=Translating caste|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PpjAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Katha|isbn=978-81-87649-05-2|pages=241}}</ref> ''Baluta'' is seen by the ''Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature'' as an attempt by the writer to be personal yet \"objective and representative\", the title generalising the status of rural [[Dalit|untouchables]]. It records the writer's struggle for peace, a struggle with no chance of retaliation in \"word or deed\".<ref name=\"Datta2006\">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=The Encyclopaedia Of Indian Literature (Volume One (A To Devo)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA357|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1803-1|pages=357\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\nRao considers that ''Baluta'', as a representative of Dalit literature, wasn't just a faithful narration of the Dalit experience but also an \"ethical challenge\" to the \"caste Hindu\" whom it \"implicated\".<ref name=\"Rao2009\">{{cite book|author=Anupama Rao|title=The caste question: Dalits and the politics of modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tDRiJ3HZVPQC&pg=PA197|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=6 July 2009|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-25761-0|pages=197\u2013}}</ref> [[Sharmila Rege]] quotes [[Urmila Pawar]], who mentions the criticism of Dalit scholars that ''Baluta'' was shameful; Urmila rejects this criticism as based on lack of understanding.<ref name=\"Rege2006\">{{cite book|first=Sharmila |last=Rege |authorlink=Sharmila Rege|title=Writing caste, writing gender: reading Dalit women's testimonios|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Msaki69NQHsC&pg=PA292|accessdate=9 March 2012|date=2 July 2006|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-81-89013-01-1|pages=292}}</ref> According to ''The Encyclopaedia...'', it created the first anti-hero in [[Marathi literature]].<ref name=\"Datta2006\"/> ''Link'' mentions that ''Baluta'' \"created a sensation in the Marathi world for its frank and unique description of a life that the author lived in the ghettos of prostitutes, criminals, pimps and uprooted Dalit people, within and around the red light areas of the city of [[Mumbai|Bombay]].\"<ref name=\"Link: Indian newsmagazine\">{{cite book|title=Link: Indian newsmagazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=89YxAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=9 March 2012|year=1981|page=37}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian autobiographies]]\n[[Category:Dalit literature]]\n", "name_user": "RileyBugz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReactions:\"wasn't\" -> \"was not\" perMOS:CONTRACT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baluta_(autobiography)"}
{"title_page": "James O'Keefe (cardiologist)", "text_new": "{{about||the American political activist|James O'Keefe|the Irish politician|James O'Keeffe}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:James H. O'Keefe, MD.jpg|thumb|James H. O'Keefe, MD]]\n'''James O'Keefe Jr.''' (born June 8, 1956) is an American author and [[cardiologist]] who has conducted studies in the field of cardiovascular medicine, diet and exercise. O'Keefe is a leading proponent of exercise but argues that moderate rather than extreme efforts, in a social setting-like are best for conferring longevity. He has also proposed a hypothesis regarding the evolutionary basis of homosexuality. He is currently a professor of medicine at the [[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City]], Director of Preventive Cardiology at the Mid America Heart Institute of Saint Luke's hospital and Chief Medical Officer of the health supplement company Cardiotabs.\n\n==Career==\nJames Henry O'Keefe Jr. was born to James Henry O'Keefe Sr. and Leatrice O\u2019Keefe in [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]], on June 8, 1956. He graduated from the [[University of North Dakota]] where he received an undergraduate BS ''summa cum laude'' and [[Phi Beta Kappa]] in Natural Science. In 1982, he received his MD ''summa cum laude'' with his MD from [[Baylor College of Medicine]]. He was a member of [[Alpha Omega Alpha]].\n\nO'Keefe completed his medical residency as well as a CV fellowship at the Mayo Graduate School of Medicine in Rochester, Minnesota.<ref name=\"cc-pc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiowellnesscenter.org/providers/james_okeefe_md.aspx|title=James H O'Keefe, Jr, MD|publisher=Saint Luke's Health Systems|accessdate=September 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627051434/http://www.cardiowellnesscenter.org/Providers/James_OKeefe_MD.aspx|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the Mid America Heart Institute, he was involved with patient care, clinical research as well as non-invasive cardiology practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http:/kc-med-web.umkc.edu/residency/radiology/pdfs/curr/Cardiac_Imaging.pdf|title=Curriculum in Cardiac Imaging|last=|first=|date=2011-07-20|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720091731/http:/kc-med-web.umkc.edu/residency/radiology/pdfs/curr/Cardiac_Imaging.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-20|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref> He has been board-certified in cardiology, nuclear cardiology, pacemakers, cholesterol management, cardiac CT imaging, and internal medicine.<ref name=\"cc-pc\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/yourlife/health/most-influential-doctors.htm|date=October 25, 2010|publisher=USA Today|title=Most Influential Doctors database|accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nO'Keefe has contributed over 358 articles to peer-reviewed medical literature.<ref>{{PubMedAuthorSearch|O'Keefe|JH}}</ref> These include his studies on the potential dangers of excessive exercise, the evolutionary basis of homosexuality, and that sugar not salt is the evil white crystal that needs to be eliminated from our diets. O'Keefe also focuses on improving  sleep, post-meal spikes in blood sugar, and fatty liver to improve health and well-being.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2007.10.016 |pmid=18206731 |title=Dietary Strategies for Improving Post-Prandial Glucose, Lipids, Inflammation, and Cardiovascular Health |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=51 |issue=3 |pages=249\u201355 |year=2008 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Gheewala |first2=Neil M |last3=O'Keefe |first3=Joan O }}</ref> He has been the lead author of several books, including, the ''Complete Guide to ECGs'', ''The Forever Young Diet & Lifestyle'' and ''Let Me Tell You a Story''.\n\n==Hunter-gatherer lifestyle==\nO'Keefe believes that a healthy lifestyle should include some features of the diet and activity patterns of our ancient ancestors.<ref name=\"paleo\">[http://www.slideshare.net/ancestralhealth/ances-health-james-okeefe-9225415]</ref> He argues that this is essential because our nutritional needs were established many centuries ago in the remote pre-historic past; thus humans have been genetically adapted to thrive in a [[Hunter-Gatherer]] type of lifestyle.<ref name=\"paleo\" /> O\u2019Keefe believes this mismatch between the diet and lifestyle for which we are genetically adapted, and the very different conditions in which we are living, is the underlying cause for much disease, disability and unhappiness. Our ancestors survived on a diet high in fish, nuts, fruits, vegetables, wild game meat and bones. They also received a large amount of exercise from walking, bending, lifting, carrying, swimming, climbing, and other activities that were necessary to their daily routines.<ref>{{YouTube|sBVlXOliI8M|Dr. James O'Keefe on How to Live a Heart Healthy Lifestyle}}</ref> O\u2019Keefe recommends beverages including water, sparkling water, green tea and coffee; also, red wine can be a healthy choice if used in moderation.<ref>{{YouTube|KOc-susXfVY|Dr. James O'Keefe on The Best Diet for Preventing Heart Disease}}</ref>\n\n== Evolutionary basis of homosexuality ==\nO\u2019Keefe gave a TEDx Talk in October 2016, on the natural origin of homosexuality. In this talk, and subsequent scientific paper, he proposes a theory about the evolutionary basis of homosexuality mediated by epigenetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glreview.org/article/evolutionary-origins-of-homosexuality/|title=Evolutionary Origins of Homosexuality|last=O\u2019Keefe JH, O\u2019Keefe EL, Hodes J|first=|date=2018|website=The Gay & Lesbian Review|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>  This theory posits that homosexuality is a naturally intended, normal variant that evolved to improve the interconnectedness and resilience of the family. The suite of psychological traits that tend to co-occur with same-sex orientation include increased IQ, and higher emotional intelligence, with less physical aggression. Through a complex interplay of epigenetics and genetics, homosexuality occurs more often in larger families, especially in a baby boy with multiple older brothers, or at times of increased stress during the pregnancy. In these settings, homosexuality is prescribed by nature largely via epigenetic changes in the developing fetus in response to the mother's environment. This can help to reduce overpopulation pressures at the family level; the gay individual also tends to improve the emotional bonding of their family and friends, thereby improving the strength survivability of the group.\n\n== Research ==\nO'Keefe's research and publications have focused mostly on exercise, diet and evolution.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2008.08.050 |pmid=19055985 |title=Vitamin D Deficiency |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=52 |issue=24 |pages=1949\u201356 |year=2008 |last1=Lee |first1=John H |last2=O'Keefe |first2=James H |last3=Bell |first3=David |last4=Hensrud |first4=Donald D |last5=Holick |first5=Michael F }}</ref> Daily exercise is one of the key components of lifestyle for promoting health and longevity, and will reduce risks for heart disease, Alzheimer's, hypertension, osteoporosis, depression and diabetes dramatically. However, excessive endurance exercise may potentially cause CV damage.<ref name=pmid22677079>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2012.04.005 |pmid=22677079 |pmc=3538475 |title=Potential Adverse Cardiovascular Effects from Excessive Endurance Exercise |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=87 |issue=6 |pages=587\u201395 |year=2012 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Patil |first2=Harshal R |last3=Lavie |first3=Carl J |last4=Magalski |first4=Anthony |last5=Vogel |first5=Robert A |last6=McCullough |first6=Peter A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2014.07.007 |pmid=25128073 |title=Exercising for Health and Longevity vs Peak Performance: Different Regimens for Different Goals |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=89 |issue=9 |pages=1171\u20135 |year=2014 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Franklin |first2=Barry |last3=Lavie |first3=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref> This work has garnered attention in both the cardiology world and the general public. The articles suggest that extreme endurance exercise such as marathons, ironman distance triathlons, and long distance bicycle races may, over many years to decades, in some individuals lead to adverse structural changes in the heart and large arteries, predisposing to \"cardiac overuse injury.\"<ref name=pmid22677079/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2015.08.001 |pmid=26362561 |title=Effects of Running on Chronic Diseases and Cardiovascular and All-Cause Mortality |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=90 |issue=11 |pages=1541\u201352 |year=2015 |last1=Lavie |first1=Carl J |last2=Lee |first2=Duck-Chul |last3=Sui |first3=Xuemei |last4=Arena |first4=Ross |last5=O'Keefe |first5=James H |last6=Church |first6=Timothy S |last7=Milani |first7=Richard V |last8=Blair |first8=Steven N |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2015.04.023 |pmid=26088316 |title=Reply |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=65 |issue=24 |pages=2674\u20132676 |year=2015 |last1=Schnohr |first1=Peter |last2=Marott |first2=Jacob L |last3=O'Keefe |first3=James H |doi-access=free }}</ref>  CV damage can include [[fibrosis]] (scarring) in the heart muscle, accelerated plaque buildup in coronary arteries and atrial fibrillation. These papers emphasize that exercise best confers benefits to longevity and cardiac health at moderate doses.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2014.11.023 |pmid=25660917 |title=Dose of Jogging and Long-Term Mortality |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=65 |issue=5 |pages=411\u20139 |year=2015 |last1=Schnohr |first1=Peter |last2=O'Keefe |first2=James H |last3=Marott |first3=Jacob L |last4=Lange |first4=Peter |last5=Jensen |first5=Gorm B |doi-access=free }}</ref> O'Keefe discusses this in a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx Talk]] entitled: \"Run for your life! At a comfortable pace and not too far.\"\n\nO'Keefe has published papers on the CV impact of both coffee and alcohol showing evidence that supports moderate consumption of either or both substances can be potentially heart healthy. Habitual light to moderate alcohol intake (up to 1 drink per day for women and 1 or 2 drinks per day for men) is associated with decreased risks for total mortality, coronary artery disease, diabetes mellitus, congestive heart failure, and stroke. However, higher levels of alcohol consumption are associated with increased CV risk.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2013.11.005 |pmid=24582196 |title=Alcohol and Cardiovascular Health: The Dose Makes the Poison\u2026or the Remedy |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=89 |issue=3 |pages=382\u201393 |year=2014 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Bhatti |first2=Salman K |last3=Bajwa |first3=Ata |last4=Dinicolantonio |first4=James J |last5=Lavie |first5=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref> Coffee consumption may reduce the risk of CV death, type 2 diabetes mellitus, suicide and Parkinson's disease.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2013.06.035 |pmid=23871889 |title=Effects of Habitual Coffee Consumption on Cardiometabolic Disease, Cardiovascular Health, and All-Cause Mortality |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=62 |issue=12 |pages=1043\u20131051 |year=2013 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Bhatti |first2=Salman K |last3=Patil |first3=Harshal R |last4=Dinicolantonio |first4=James J |last5=Lucan |first5=Sean C |last6=Lavie |first6=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he published an article about an evidence-based approach to the ideal diet for health and longevity.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2017.12.001 |pmid=29406200 |title=Evidence, Not Evangelism, for Dietary Recommendations |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=93 |issue=2 |pages=138\u2013144 |year=2018 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Dinicolantonio |first2=James J |last3=Sigurdsson |first3=Axel F |last4=Ros |first4=Emilio }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he published a paper entitled ''Nutritional strategies for skeletal and cardiovascular health: hard bones, soft arteries, rather than vice versa.'' This paper showed that calcium is ideally obtained from dietary sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http:/thepaleodiet.com/got-bones-paleo-solution-building-strong-bones-keeping-arteries-soft-supple/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905185205/http:/thepaleodiet.com/got-bones-paleo-solution-building-strong-bones-keeping-arteries-soft-supple/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-05|title=Got Bones? The Paleo Solution for Building Strong Bones : The Paleo Diet\u2122|date=2015-09-05|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>  The form of calcium in bones and bone meal is calcium-hydroxyapatite, which may be particularly effective for building bone.  Increased consumption of calcium-rich foods such as bones, fermented dairy products (e.g. yogurt, kefir, cheese), leafy greens, almonds, and chia seeds may be effective for improving both skeletal and CV health.\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Keefe has a family legacy in the medicine profession.  His great-grandfather, Henry O'Keefe, practiced medicine in North Dakota from 1890 to 1935. Henry's son, Emmett (James' grandfather), was also a doctor in North Dakota.\n\nO'Keefe met his wife, Joan, while at the [[Mayo Clinic]]. The two married in October 1984 and together they have four children: James III, Evan, Kathleen, and Caroline. Evan started medical school in January 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*DiNicolantonio JJ, Mehta V, O'Keefe. Is Salt a Culprit or an Innocent Bystander in Hypertension? A Hypothesis Challenging the Ancient Paradigm. The American Journal of Medicine. 2017;130(8):892-99.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, Hammill SC, Freed M, The Complete Guide to ECGs. Jones and Bartlett Publishing. 2015.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, O\u2019Keefe J: Let Me Tell You a Story. Andrews McMeel Universal, Kansas City, MO, March, 2013.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, O\u2019Keefe J: The Forever Young Diet and Lifestyle. Andrews McMeel Universal, Kansas City, MO, November 2005.\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/openhrt-2015-000300 |pmid=26468402 |pmc=4600246 |title=The health benefits of vitamin K |journal=Open Heart |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=e000300 |year=2015 |last1=Dinicolantonio |first1=James J |last2=Bhutani |first2=Jaikrit |last3=O'Keefe |first3=James H }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/openhrt-2015-000325 |pmid=27042317 |pmc=4809188 |title=Nutritional strategies for skeletal and cardiovascular health: Hard bones, soft arteries, rather than vice versa |journal=Open Heart |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=e000325 |year=2016 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Bergman |first2=Nathaniel |last3=Carrera-Bastos |first3=Pedro |last4=Fontes-Villalba |first4=Ma\u00e9lan |last5=Dinicolantonio |first5=James J |last6=Cordain |first6=Loren }}\n*DiNicolantonio JJ, Lucan SC, O\u2019Keefe JH:  The evidence for saturated fat and for sugar related to coronary heart disease.  Prog Cardiovasc Dis. 2016 Jan-Feb;58(4):401-6. Epub ahead of print 2015 November. 2016 Mar-Apr;58(5):464-472. 2016 March\u2013April.\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.pcad.2016.01.007 |pmid=26892393 |title=Computed Tomography for Coronary Artery Calcification Scoring: Mammogram for the Heart |journal=Progress in Cardiovascular Diseases |volume=58 |issue=5 |pages=529\u201336 |year=2016 |last1=Qazi |first1=Abdul H |last2=Zallaghi |first2=Forough |last3=Torres-Acosta |first3=Noel |last4=Thompson |first4=Randall C |last5=O'Keefe |first5=James H }}\n*O\u2019Keefe JH, DiNicolantonio JJ, Lavie CJ: Statins, ezetimibe, and proprotein convertase subtilsin-kexin Type 9 (PCSK9) inhibitors to reduce low-density lipoprotein-cholesterol and cardiovascular events.  Am J Cardiol. Publication in 2017 January.\n*O\u2019Keefe JH, Jacob D, Lavie CJ: Omega-3 fatty acid therapy: The tide turns for a fish story.  Mayo Clin Proc. Am J Cardiol. Publication in 2017 January.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y6U728AZnV0 TEDx Talk, Run for your life! At a comfortable pace, and not too far.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100327184417/http://www.foreveryoungdiet.com/ The Forever Young Diet and Lifestyle]\n* [http://cardiotabs.com CardioTabs]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100417042951/http://www.cc-pc.com/ Saint Luke's Cardiovascular Consultants]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101225162730/http://www.cardiotabs.com/download/OKeefe_Publications.pdf Complete Research Publication List]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Khn_z9FPmU TEDx Talk, Homosexuality: It\u2019s about survival-not sex]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okeefe, James, Md}}\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:University of North Dakota alumni]]\n[[Category:Baylor College of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:Physicians from North Dakota]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the American political activist|James O'Keefe|the Irish politician|James O'Keeffe}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:James H. O'Keefe, MD.jpg|thumb|James H. O'Keefe, MD]]\n'''James O'Keefe Jr.''' (born June 8, 1956) is an American author and [[cardiologist]] who has conducted studies in the field of cardiovascular medicine, diet and exercise. O'Keefe is a leading proponent of exercise but argues that moderate rather than extreme efforts, in a social setting-like are best for conferring longevity. He has also proposed a hypothesis regarding the evolutionary basis of homosexuality. He is currently a professor of medicine at the [[University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City]], Director of Preventive Cardiology at the Mid America Heart Institute of Saint Luke's hospital and Chief Medical Officer of the health supplement company Cardiotabs.\n\n==Career==\nJames Henry O'Keefe Jr. was born to James Henry O'Keefe Sr. and Leatrice O\u2019Keefe in [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]], on June 8, 1956. He graduated from the [[University of North Dakota]] where he received an undergraduate BS ''summa cum laude'' and [[Phi Beta Kappa]] in Natural Science. In 1982, he received his MD ''summa cum laude'' with his MD from [[Baylor College of Medicine]]. He was a member of [[Alpha Omega Alpha]].\n\nO'Keefe completed his medical residency as well as a CV fellowship at the Mayo Graduate School of Medicine in Rochester, Minnesota.<ref name=\"cc-pc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiowellnesscenter.org/providers/james_okeefe_md.aspx|title=James H O'Keefe, Jr, MD|publisher=Saint Luke's Health Systems|accessdate=September 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627051434/http://www.cardiowellnesscenter.org/Providers/James_OKeefe_MD.aspx|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the Mid America Heart Institute, he was involved with patient care, clinical research as well as non-invasive cardiology practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http:/kc-med-web.umkc.edu/residency/radiology/pdfs/curr/Cardiac_Imaging.pdf|title=Curriculum in Cardiac Imaging|last=|first=|date=2011-07-20|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720091731/http:/kc-med-web.umkc.edu/residency/radiology/pdfs/curr/Cardiac_Imaging.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-20|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref> He has been board-certified in cardiology, nuclear cardiology, pacemakers, cholesterol management, cardiac CT imaging, and internal medicine.<ref name=\"cc-pc\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/yourlife/health/most-influential-doctors.htm|date=October 25, 2010|publisher=USA Today|title=Most Influential Doctors database|accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nO'Keefe has contributed over 358 articles to peer-reviewed medical literature.<ref>{{PubMedAuthorSearch|O'Keefe|JH}}</ref> These include his studies on the potential dangers of excessive exercise, the evolutionary basis of homosexuality, and that sugar not salt is the evil white crystal that needs to be eliminated from our diets. O'Keefe also focuses on improving  sleep, post-meal spikes in blood sugar, and fatty liver to improve health and well-being.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2007.10.016 |pmid=18206731 |title=Dietary Strategies for Improving Post-Prandial Glucose, Lipids, Inflammation, and Cardiovascular Health |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=51 |issue=3 |pages=249\u201355 |year=2008 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Gheewala |first2=Neil M |last3=O'Keefe |first3=Joan O }}</ref> He has been the lead author of several books, including, the ''Complete Guide to ECGs'', ''The Forever Young Diet & Lifestyle'' and ''Let Me Tell You a Story''.\n\n==Hunter-gatherer lifestyle==\nO'Keefe believes that a healthy lifestyle should include some features of the diet and activity patterns of our ancient ancestors.<ref name=\"paleo\">[http://www.slideshare.net/ancestralhealth/ances-health-james-okeefe-9225415]</ref> He argues that this is essential because our nutritional needs were established many centuries ago in the remote pre-historic past; thus humans have been genetically adapted to thrive in a [[Hunter-Gatherer]] type of lifestyle.<ref name=\"paleo\" /> O\u2019Keefe believes this mismatch between the diet and lifestyle for which we are genetically adapted, and the very different conditions in which we are living, is the underlying cause for much disease, disability and unhappiness. Our ancestors survived on a diet high in fish, nuts, fruits, vegetables, wild game meat and bones. They also received a large amount of exercise from walking, bending, lifting, carrying, swimming, climbing, and other activities that were necessary to their daily routines.<ref>{{YouTube|sBVlXOliI8M|Dr. James O'Keefe on How to Live a Heart Healthy Lifestyle}}</ref> O\u2019Keefe recommends beverages including water, sparkling water, green tea and coffee; also, red wine can be a healthy choice if used in moderation.<ref>{{YouTube|KOc-susXfVY|Dr. James O'Keefe on The Best Diet for Preventing Heart Disease}}</ref>\n\n== Evolutionary basis of homosexuality ==\nO\u2019Keefe gave a TEDx Talk in October 2016, on the natural origin of homosexuality. In this talk, and subsequent scientific paper, he proposes a theory about the evolutionary basis of homosexuality mediated by epigenetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glreview.org/article/evolutionary-origins-of-homosexuality/|title=Evolutionary Origins of Homosexuality|last=O\u2019Keefe JH, O\u2019Keefe EL, Hodes J|first=|date=2018|website=The Gay & Lesbian Review|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>  This theory posits that homosexuality is a naturally intended, normal variant that evolved to improve the interconnectedness and resilience of the family. The suite of psychological traits that tend to co-occur with same-sex orientation include increased IQ, and higher emotional intelligence, with less physical aggression. Through a complex interplay of epigenetics and genetics, homosexuality occurs more often in larger families, especially in a baby boy with multiple older brothers, or at times of increased stress during the pregnancy. In these settings, homosexuality is prescribed by nature largely via epigenetic changes in the developing fetus in response to the mother's environment. This can help to reduce overpopulation pressures at the family level; the gay individual also tends to improve the emotional bonding of their family and friends, thereby improving the strength survivability of the group.\n\n== Research ==\nO'Keefe's research and publications have focused mostly on exercise, diet and evolution.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2008.08.050 |pmid=19055985 |title=Vitamin D Deficiency |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=52 |issue=24 |pages=1949\u201356 |year=2008 |last1=Lee |first1=John H |last2=O'Keefe |first2=James H |last3=Bell |first3=David |last4=Hensrud |first4=Donald D |last5=Holick |first5=Michael F }}</ref> Daily exercise is one of the key components of lifestyle for promoting health and longevity, and will reduce risks for heart disease, Alzheimer's, hypertension, osteoporosis, depression and diabetes dramatically. However, excessive endurance exercise may potentially cause CV damage.<ref name=pmid22677079>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2012.04.005 |pmid=22677079 |pmc=3538475 |title=Potential Adverse Cardiovascular Effects from Excessive Endurance Exercise |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=87 |issue=6 |pages=587\u201395 |year=2012 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Patil |first2=Harshal R |last3=Lavie |first3=Carl J |last4=Magalski |first4=Anthony |last5=Vogel |first5=Robert A |last6=McCullough |first6=Peter A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2014.07.007 |pmid=25128073 |title=Exercising for Health and Longevity vs Peak Performance: Different Regimens for Different Goals |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=89 |issue=9 |pages=1171\u20135 |year=2014 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Franklin |first2=Barry |last3=Lavie |first3=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref> This work has garnered attention in both the cardiology world and the general public. The articles suggest that extreme endurance exercise such as marathons, ironman distance triathlons, and long distance bicycle races may, over many years to decades, in some individuals lead to adverse structural changes in the heart and large arteries, predisposing to \"cardiac overuse injury.\"<ref name=pmid22677079/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2015.08.001 |pmid=26362561 |title=Effects of Running on Chronic Diseases and Cardiovascular and All-Cause Mortality |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=90 |issue=11 |pages=1541\u201352 |year=2015 |last1=Lavie |first1=Carl J |last2=Lee |first2=Duck-Chul |last3=Sui |first3=Xuemei |last4=Arena |first4=Ross |last5=O'Keefe |first5=James H |last6=Church |first6=Timothy S |last7=Milani |first7=Richard V |last8=Blair |first8=Steven N |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2015.04.023 |pmid=26088316 |title=Reply |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=65 |issue=24 |pages=2674\u20132676 |year=2015 |last1=Schnohr |first1=Peter |last2=Marott |first2=Jacob L |last3=O'Keefe |first3=James H |doi-access=free }}</ref>  CV damage can include [[fibrosis]] (scarring) in the heart muscle, accelerated plaque buildup in coronary arteries and atrial fibrillation. These papers emphasize that exercise best confers benefits to longevity and cardiac health at moderate doses.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2014.11.023 |pmid=25660917 |title=Dose of Jogging and Long-Term Mortality |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=65 |issue=5 |pages=411\u20139 |year=2015 |last1=Schnohr |first1=Peter |last2=O'Keefe |first2=James H |last3=Marott |first3=Jacob L |last4=Lange |first4=Peter |last5=Jensen |first5=Gorm B |doi-access=free }}</ref> O'Keefe discusses this in a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx Talk]] entitled: \"Run for your life! At a comfortable pace and not too far.\"\n\nO'Keefe has published papers on the CV impact of both coffee and alcohol showing evidence that supports moderate consumption of either or both substances can be potentially heart healthy. Habitual light to moderate alcohol intake (up to 1 drink per day for women and 1 or 2 drinks per day for men) is associated with decreased risks for total mortality, coronary artery disease, diabetes mellitus, congestive heart failure, and stroke. However, higher levels of alcohol consumption are associated with increased CV risk.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2013.11.005 |pmid=24582196 |title=Alcohol and Cardiovascular Health: The Dose Makes the Poison\u2026or the Remedy |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=89 |issue=3 |pages=382\u201393 |year=2014 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Bhatti |first2=Salman K |last3=Bajwa |first3=Ata |last4=Dinicolantonio |first4=James J |last5=Lavie |first5=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref> Coffee consumption may reduce the risk of CV death, type 2 diabetes mellitus, suicide and Parkinson's disease.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2013.06.035 |pmid=23871889 |title=Effects of Habitual Coffee Consumption on Cardiometabolic Disease, Cardiovascular Health, and All-Cause Mortality |journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology |volume=62 |issue=12 |pages=1043\u20131051 |year=2013 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Bhatti |first2=Salman K |last3=Patil |first3=Harshal R |last4=Dinicolantonio |first4=James J |last5=Lucan |first5=Sean C |last6=Lavie |first6=Carl J |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he published an article about an evidence-based approach to the ideal diet for health and longevity.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2017.12.001 |pmid=29406200 |title=Evidence, Not Evangelism, for Dietary Recommendations |journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings |volume=93 |issue=2 |pages=138\u2013144 |year=2018 |last1=O'Keefe |first1=James H |last2=Dinicolantonio |first2=James J |last3=Sigurdsson |first3=Axel F |last4=Ros |first4=Emilio }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he published a paper entitled ''Nutritional strategies for skeletal and cardiovascular health: hard bones, soft arteries, rather than vice versa.'' This paper showed that calcium is ideally obtained from dietary sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http:/thepaleodiet.com/got-bones-paleo-solution-building-strong-bones-keeping-arteries-soft-supple/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905185205/http:/thepaleodiet.com/got-bones-paleo-solution-building-strong-bones-keeping-arteries-soft-supple/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-05|title=Got Bones? The Paleo Solution for Building Strong Bones : The Paleo Diet\u2122|date=2015-09-05|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>  The form of calcium in bones and bone meal is calcium-hydroxyapatite, which may be particularly effective for building bone.  Increased consumption of calcium-rich foods such as bones, fermented dairy products (e.g. yogurt, kefir, cheese), leafy greens, almonds, and chia seeds may be effective for improving both skeletal and CV health.\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Keefe has a family legacy in the medicine profession.  His great grandfather, Henry O'Keefe, practiced medicine in North Dakota from 1890 to 1935. Henry's son, Emmett (James' grandfather), was also a doctor in North Dakota.\n\nO'Keefe met his wife, Joan, while at the [[Mayo Clinic]]. The two married in October 1984 and together they have four children: James III, Evan, Kathleen, and Caroline. Evan started medical school in January 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*DiNicolantonio JJ, Mehta V, O'Keefe. Is Salt a Culprit or an Innocent Bystander in Hypertension? A Hypothesis Challenging the Ancient Paradigm. The American Journal of Medicine. 2017;130(8):892-99.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, Hammill SC, Freed M, The Complete Guide to ECGs. Jones and Bartlett Publishing. 2015.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, O\u2019Keefe J: Let Me Tell You a Story. Andrews McMeel Universal, Kansas City, MO, March, 2013.\n*O'Keefe JH Jr, O\u2019Keefe J: The Forever Young Diet and Lifestyle. Andrews McMeel Universal, Kansas City, MO, November 2005.\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/openhrt-2015-000300 |pmid=26468402 |pmc=4600246 |title=The health benefits of vitamin K |journal=Open Heart |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=e000300 |year=2015 |last1=Dinicolantonio |first1=James J |last2=Bhutani |first2=Jaikrit |last3=O'Keefe |first3=James H }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/openhrt-2015-000325 |pmid=27042317 |pmc=4809188 |title=Nutritional strategies for skeletal and cardiovascular health: Hard bones, soft arteries, rather than vice versa |journal=Open Heart |v